Background Information: Domain Knowledge and Information Sources¶

Most of us have stayed at an Airbnb, right? Some have beeen cheap but some have been freakingly expensive.

What drives the price of an Airbnb? This is what we'll find out in this notebook.

We found some data gold in the form of this Kaggle Airbnb Boston dataset (link)

From their own description: The following Airbnb activity is included in this Boston dataset: Listings, including full descriptions and average review score Reviews, including unique id for each reviewer and detailed comments * Calendar, including listing id and the price and availability for that day

Questions to be answered¶

How do price vary in the different neighborhoods?

What elements are correleated with price?

What's the impact on price of for example, # guests to accomodate, number of ratings, rating, etc?

Data Wranglig, cleaning, and preparation¶

Listings

Some columns may not be so relevant

More cities than just Boston included

Amenities: all included as a list

missing values in many columns and rows

host_listings_count, host_total_listings_count, accommodates, bathrooms as float instead of int

Price as string (includes dollar sign)

Response time is string and not float

Reducing our dataset - Which columns do we care about?¶

If our objective is to understand better the price, there are some columns that may not be very helpful in this (e.g. listing_url). A smaller dataset will be better for us to work with

Columns to keep¶

I went through all columns, saw what type of values there were and exercised my human judgement to keep only a subset of the columns

In [388]:
def clean_usd(df,col_name):
    '''
    INPUT
    - df : Data Frame
    - col_name (string): Column name to be clean. Should be for cols that follow this format $100.08 
    
    PROCESS
    - Fill na with string $0
    - remove $ sign
    - remove commas
    - convert to numeric
    
    OUTPUT
    - Clean df: Column Float with numeric value. Any NAs will be filled with 0
    
    '''
    import pandas as pd
    
    #Fill na with string $0
    df[col_name] = df[col_name].fillna('$0')
    
    #remove $ sign
    no_usd = lambda x: x[1:]
    df[col_name] = df[col_name].apply(no_usd)
    
    #remove commas
    no_commas = lambda x: x.replace(',','')
    df[col_name] = df[col_name].apply(no_commas)
    
    #convert to numeric
    df[col_name] = pd.to_numeric(df[col_name])
    
    return df

import sklearn.metrics as metrics
def regression_results(y_true, y_pred):
    ''' Adapted from Naomi Fridman's stackoverflow post (see link below)
    
    INPUT: 
    y_true: The original dependent variable from the testing dataset
    y_pred: The predicted depedent variable from the model
    
    OUTPUT:
    Different regression metrics. 
    r2 explains the % of variance on dependent variable that can be explained by model
    
    '''
    
    
    # Regression metrics
    explained_variance=metrics.explained_variance_score(y_true, y_pred)
    mean_absolute_error=metrics.mean_absolute_error(y_true, y_pred) 
    mse=metrics.mean_squared_error(y_true, y_pred) 
    #mean_squared_log_error=metrics.mean_squared_log_error(y_true, y_pred)
    median_absolute_error=metrics.median_absolute_error(y_true, y_pred)
    r2=metrics.r2_score(y_true, y_pred)

    print('explained_variance: ', round(explained_variance,4))    
    #print('mean_squared_log_error: ', round(mean_squared_log_error,4))
    print('r2: ', round(r2,4))
    print('MAE: ', round(mean_absolute_error,4))
    print('MSE: ', round(mse,4))
    print('RMSE: ', round(np.sqrt(mse),4))

Thanks Naomi Fridman from this Stackoverflow post

Some tokens of wisdom to extract here:

If a place can host one additional person, you can expect a price increase of 23$.

If review rating goes 1 percentage point up, you can expect an increase of 0.89 usd in the price per night. Is this much? Let's imagine you're renting a place 100 nights in a year. Your increase your score by 11 points (say, from 0.8 to 0.91) . This means that you can expect to gain 1000 USD more in that same year!

Don't want to share an apartment with others? If you have the property all for yourself, you can expect the price to increase 50 USD
